{
    "analysis": "From the prior summary: metric.csv is large (319,721 rows) and spans 2022-03-20 13:30 to 14:30 (UTC+8). trace.csv and log.csv only cover the incident window (trace: 14:00–14:29, log: 14:00–14:30). error_logs.csv is empty. Next we should follow the prescribed workflow: compute global thresholds per component-KPI (using the full metric series), then filter metric points to the incident window (2022-03-20 14:00:00 to 2022-03-20 14:30:00 UTC+8), and detect anomalies where metric values exceed their global threshold. The objective of this Executor step is to produce a compact ranked list of candidate faulty component-KPI pairs during the window so we can narrow investigation with traces and logs.\n\nWhat should be computed and returned (compact): using the full metric.csv series for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 threshold. Then restrict metric points to the incident window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 to 2022-03-20 14:30:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) report: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, number_of_points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (if any), max_value_in_window, and severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_P95 (use Inf or large number if P95==0). Return at most top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count_in_window desc then severity_ratio desc. Limit returned rows to top 20. Timestamps should be in ISO format with +08:00. Return numeric fields with reasonable precision. ",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 across the full available series. Then filter metric points to the UTC+8 time window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within that window produce a single summarized row with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (count of rows with value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO+08:00, or NA if none), max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_P95 (set to null or a large flag if global_P95==0). Return at most top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count_in_window (desc), then severity_ratio (desc). Provide the result as a compact table. Do not print raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric-level summary we computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) across the full metric series, then inspected the 2022-03-20 14:00–14:30 (UTC+8) window. The compact top-20 table shows 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs where every sample in the 31-minute window exceeded their global P95 (anomaly_count_in_window = 31, earliest anomaly = 2022-03-20T14:00:00+08:00). The strongest deviation is node-6 / system.disk.total (severity_ratio ≈ 1.6276), followed by several container file-descriptor and socket metrics associated with node-6. Many other KPIs show only slight exceedances (~1.0–1.05). This indicates a broad, sustained anomaly beginning at 14:00 affecting multiple components, with node-6 disk usage being the most significant signal. However, we still need to (1) identify distinct consecutive fault sub-series (to determine whether there were two separate failures inside the 14:00–14:30 window), (2) extract the precise start times for each fault, and (3) use traces/logs to triangulate the root-cause component and reason for each failure. The next step is to convert these per-(component,KPI) anomaly indicators into consecutive anomaly segments (faults) so we can locate exact start times and durations and narrow candidates for trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric-level top candidates table you produced and the full metric.csv time-series cached in the kernel, detect consecutive anomaly segments (faults) within the UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 for the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs (the ones returned previously). Define an anomaly point as value >= that pair's global_P95 (global_P95 already computed). Consider points consecutive if timestamps are consecutive minute steps (difference == 60 seconds). For each detected anomaly segment return one row with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, fault_start_timestamp (ISO+08:00), fault_end_timestamp (ISO+08:00), duration_minutes, points_in_segment, max_value_in_segment, severity_ratio_segment = max_value_in_segment / global_P95. Also include segment_rank_per_pair (1,2,... if multiple segments for same pair) and total_segments_for_pair. Return at most top 20 segments sorted by severity_ratio_segment (desc) then duration_minutes (desc). Do not print raw time series. Keep results compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step (metric analysis and fault identification) computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) across the full metric series, filtered metrics to the incident window 2022-03-20 14:00:00–14:30:00 (UTC+8), and detected anomaly segments. The compact top-20 shows every minute in the window (31 points) exceeded the global P95 for those pairs, with the strongest deviation being node-6 / system.disk.total (severity ≈ 1.63). All top candidates have a single continuous anomaly segment covering the entire window and earliest anomaly timestamp 2022-03-20T14:00:00+08:00. From this we can infer a sustained anomaly beginning at 14:00 that affects multiple containers and node-6 disk metrics; however, metrics alone do not yet resolve whether there are two distinct failures inside the 14:00–14:30 window nor which specific components/services are the root causes for each failure. Per the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to (1) locate which services/pods experienced anomalous traces (latency/throughput) and (2) identify downstream faulty services in call chains to help localize root-cause components for each failure event.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, compute global P95 for each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available trace series. Then filter trace points to the UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within that window, produce a summary row with these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_P95, points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (count of rows with value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO+08:00 or NA), max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_P95 (use null/flag if global_P95==0). Return at most top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count_in_window (desc) then severity_ratio (desc). Keep output compact (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From metric analysis we found many component-KPI pairs continuously exceeding their global P95 across the entire 14:00–14:30 window; the strongest signal is node-6 system.disk.total (severity ≈ 1.63) and several container-level file-descriptor/socket KPIs tied to node-6. Fault identification produced single continuous anomaly segments (start 14:00, duration 31 minutes) for top candidates, so metrics alone suggest a sustained anomaly beginning at 14:00 rather than two clearly separated faults. Trace analysis showed mostly zeros or values equal to P95 (many global_P95==0), so traces do not provide strong spike evidence or downstream-fault ordering for distinct events in the window. error_logs.csv is empty, so we must rely on log.csv and the metrics to pinpoint two failures and their exact root causes/times. The next step is to analyze log.csv for error/warn spikes and per-component error counts/timestamps in the 14:00–14:30 window to (1) identify components and precise minutes with elevated errors and (2) find candidate distinct failure times within the window. This will help determine whether there were indeed two separate failures and which components/times to inspect further.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv: (1) compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, log_name) over the full available log series. (2) Filter log points to UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive. (3) Produce two compact outputs: \nA) Top up to 20 rows (sorted by anomaly_count_in_window desc then severity desc) with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, global_P95, points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO+08:00 or NA), max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_P95 (use null/flag if global_P95==0). \nB) Aggregated per-cmdb_id error summary (limit top 10 cmdb_ids by total_error_count_in_window) with columns: cmdb_id, total_error_count_in_window (sum of log.error_count values in window), earliest_nonzero_error_timestamp_in_window (ISO+08:00 or NA), max_error_count_in_window, timestamps_of_nonzero_errors (list up to 10 timestamps ISO+08:00). \nReturn both outputs compactly; do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "From previous steps: metric analysis found many (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs continuously exceeding their global P95 across the whole 14:00–14:30 window, with strongest deviations on node-6 disk metrics and container file-descriptor/socket metrics tied to node-6. Trace and log analyses were unhelpful: many trace metrics had P95 == 0 (producing false positives) or exact-equality to P95, and log.error_count is zero across the window. Metrics point to a sustained anomaly beginning at 14:00 rather than obvious two distinct faults. However, the incident report claims two failures in this 14:00–14:30 interval. To resolve whether there were two separate failures, we must search beyond the top-20 metric candidates for any component-KPI that shows (a) multiple disjoint anomaly segments in the window or (b) earliest anomaly start time later than 14:00 (indicating a separate event). Finding any pairs with multiple segments or different start times will let us isolate two distinct failure times and then use trace/log focus around each to localize root causes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan ALL (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs in metric.csv. For each pair: (1) compute global P95 using the full available series for that pair; (2) filter to the UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive; (3) detect anomaly segments within the window where value >= global_P95 and consecutive timestamps differ by 60s. For each pair return a compact row containing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, points_in_window, total_segments_for_pair, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO+08:00 or NA), first_segment_start (ISO+08:00), first_segment_end (ISO+08:00), first_segment_duration_minutes, second_segment_start (ISO+08:00 or NA), second_segment_end (ISO+08:00 or NA), second_segment_duration_minutes (or NA), max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_P95 (null/flag if global_P95==0). Only return rows where total_segments_for_pair > 1 OR earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window != '2022-03-20T14:00:00+0800'. Limit output to top 20 rows sorted by total_segments_for_pair (desc) then earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (asc). Keep results compact and do not print raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps (metric -> fault identification -> trace -> log) computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and found many metrics continuously exceeding their P95 across the entire 2022-03-20 14:00–14:30 (UTC+8) window. The strongest metric signal was node-6/system.disk.total (severity ≈ 1.63). Trace metrics and logs provided little useful signal (many P95==0 or exact matches; error_logs.csv is empty; log.error_count == 0 across window). Metrics indicate a sustained anomaly starting at 14:00 rather than clearly separated two failures. To determine whether there were actually two distinct failures in the 14:00–14:30 interval, we need a focused, compact scan of all metric pairs to find any that show (A) earliest anomaly timestamp strictly after 14:00 (which would indicate a later, separate event), or (B) multiple disjoint anomaly segments within the window. The Executor previously failed on a broad multi-field extraction; we should ask a narrower, bounded aggregation: counts of pairs by earliest anomaly time category and examples of candidate pairs with later starts or multiple segments (limit 10).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan all (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs in metric.csv. For each pair: compute global P95 using the full available series for that pair; then filter points to UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive and detect anomaly points where value >= global_P95. Identify consecutive anomaly segments where adjacent timestamps differ by 60 seconds. Return a compact summary with: \n1) Overall counts: total_number_of_pairs_scanned; number_of_pairs_with_any_anomaly_in_window; number_of_pairs_with_earliest_anomaly_at_2022-03-20T14:00:00+08:00; number_of_pairs_with_earliest_anomaly_after_2022-03-20T14:00:00+08:00; number_of_pairs_with_more_than_one_segment_in_window. \n2) Up to 10 example rows (limit 10) for pairs that either have earliest_anomaly_after_14:00 or total_segments_for_pair>1. For each example row return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, points_in_window, total_segments_for_pair, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (ISO+08:00 or NA), first_segment_start (ISO+08:00), first_segment_end (ISO+08:00), second_segment_start (ISO+08:00 or NA), second_segment_end (ISO+08:00 or NA), max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_P95 (or null/flag if global_P95==0). Sort examples by earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window ascending then severity_ratio descending. Keep outputs compact and limit rows as specified. Do not print raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We scanned all 5,253 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs and computed global P95 per pair using the full metric series, then inspected the UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00:00–14:30:00. Results show a broad system-wide shift at 14:00:00 where 3,834 pairs had their earliest anomaly exactly at 14:00 and 5,149 pairs had anomalies in the window. Importantly, 1,315 pairs began after 14:00 and 1,181 pairs show multiple separate anomaly segments inside the window. Example candidates show later earliest anomalies at 14:03:00 and 14:04:00 and repeated segments (e.g., node-5 nofile at 14:03 and 14:07, emailservice2-0 at 14:04 and 14:11, cartservice-1 threads with repeated peaks). This pattern implies at least one large, immediate event at 14:00 plus intermittent or secondary events later (notably around 14:03–14:05 and around 14:11). Traces and logs so far provided little direct signal (many P95==0 or zero error counts). To pinpoint the two failures' precise occurrence datetimes and root-cause components we need to (1) find the exact minute(s) where the anomaly footprint changes (distinct peaks or shifts) across components, and (2) inspect which components (node or pod) contribute most to those minute-level changes. A compact per-minute anomaly footprint will reveal candidate minute boundaries for the two failures and rank components to prioritize for trace/log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously used global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) (compute P95 across each pair's full series if not cached):\n1) For each minute in UTC+8 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive, count the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs where value >= that pair's global_P95. Produce a table with one row per minute: minute_timestamp (ISO+08:00), anomalous_pairs_count.\n2) For each minute also list the top 5 cmdb_ids that contributed the most anomalous pairs in that minute, with counts per cmdb_id. For each minute include a compact field top5_cmdb_id_counts listing up to 5 items like cmdb_id:count (limit to top 5). \n3) Additionally return a short summary of the top 5 minutes by anomalous_pairs_count (sorted desc) with their timestamps and counts.\nKeep the output compact (31 minute rows max) and do not print raw time series. Use the anomaly definition value >= global_P95 computed from full-series P95 per pair."
}

{
    "analysis": "You scanned all 5,253 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs and computed global P95 per pair (using the full series), then inspected the UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00–14:30. Findings: a large system-wide shift at 14:00 where 3,834 pairs had earliest anomaly exactly at 14:00; overall 5,149 pairs showed anomalies in the window. Crucially, 1,315 pairs begin after 14:00 and 1,181 pairs have multiple disjoint anomaly segments inside the window. Example candidate highlights show secondary activity around 14:03–14:05 and around 14:11 (e.g., node-5 nofile at 14:03 and 14:07; emailservice2-0 at 14:04 and 14:11; cartservice-1 threads with repeated peaks). This implies at least one major event at 14:00 and additional intermittent/secondary events later in the window. Traces and logs gave little direct signal (many P95==0 traces; log.error_count == 0; error_logs empty). To separate the two failures and assign precise occurrence minutes, we must inspect minute-level anomaly footprints to see which minutes concentrate anomalous pairs and which components contribute most at those minutes. That will produce candidate exact failure minutes to investigate with traces/logs next.",
