    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) computed from each pair's full series (compute if not cached):\n1) For each minute in UTC+8 from 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive, count the number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs whose value >= that pair's global_P95. Produce a table with two columns: minute_timestamp (ISO+08:00) and anomalous_pairs_count. Return all minute rows (up to 31 rows).\n2) From that result, identify the top 3 minutes by anomalous_pairs_count (sorted desc). For each of these top 3 minutes, list the top 5 cmdb_ids that contributed the most anomalous pairs in that minute, with counts per cmdb_id, formatted compactly as cmdb_id:count (limit 5 per minute).\nReturn both outputs compactly: the full per-minute table (31 rows) and the top-3-minute breakdown with top-5 contributing cmdb_ids per minute. Do not print raw time series or other data."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold calculation and broad metric/trace/log scans. Metrics show a system-wide shift beginning at 2022-03-20T14:00:00+08:00 affecting thousands of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs; many pairs also show secondary/intermittent anomaly segments later in the window (notably around 14:03–14:05 and ~14:11). Traces and logs are unhelpful so far (many P95==0 and log.error_count==0). To identify the two failures we must (a) pick the exact minute boundaries where the anomaly footprint changes (candidate failure minutes) and (b) determine which components dominate the anomaly footprint at those minutes. The metric scan produced candidate minutes (14:00, 14:03, 14:04, 14:07, 14:11). We still need compact per-minute anomaly counts and per-minute top contributing components to decide two precise failure minutes to investigate further with traces/logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Compute compact minute-level anomaly counts and top contributors for selected minutes.\n1) Using metric.csv and each pair's global P95 computed from the full series (compute if not cached), for these specific UTC+8 timestamps: 2022-03-20T14:00:00+08:00, 2022-03-20T14:03:00+08:00, 2022-03-20T14:04:00+08:00, 2022-03-20T14:07:00+08:00, 2022-03-20T14:11:00+08:00, compute: minute_timestamp (ISO+08:00) and anomalous_pairs_count (count of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) where value >= global_P95 at that minute).\n2) For each of those minutes, also return the top 5 cmdb_ids contributing anomalous pairs at that minute with counts, formatted as cmdb_id:count (limit to top 5). \n3) Additionally return the single minute (within 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 14:30:00 UTC+8) that has the maximum anomalous_pairs_count and provide its timestamp and count.\nKeep all outputs compact and bounded (6 minute rows for the selected list plus one top-minute result). Do not print raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed per-minute anomalous-pair counts across 2022-03-20 14:00–14:30 (UTC+8). Results show a very large system-wide anomaly footprint beginning at 14:00 with thousands of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs exceeding their per-pair global P95 across the window and a peak at 14:30. Top contributing services in sampled minutes are adservice/adservice2 and frontends. From the earlier full-pair scan we also saw many pairs with multiple disjoint segments and a nontrivial number of pairs whose earliest anomaly occurred after 14:00 (notably around 14:03–14:05 and ~14:11). This pattern suggests (at minimum) a major event at or immediately before 14:00 and additional secondary/intermittent events later in the window. To pinpoint the two failure occurrence minutes (the likely first-occurrence minutes) we should look for minutes with the largest minute-to-minute increases in anomalous_pairs_count (spikes), then inspect which components dominate those spike minutes to localize likely root-cause components for each failure. The next Executor step will therefore compute minute-to-minute deltas and report the top increase minutes and their top contributing components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) global P95 thresholds (compute P95 per pair from the full series if not already cached), do the following for the UTC+8 window 2022-03-20 14:00:00 through 2022-03-20 14:30:00 inclusive: \n1) For each minute compute anomalous_pairs_count = number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs with value >= that pair's global_P95 at that minute. \n2) Compute minute_to_minute_delta for each minute = anomalous_pairs_count(current_minute) - anomalous_pairs_count(previous_minute). (For 14:00 use previous_minute delta = anomalous_pairs_count(14:00) - anomalous_pairs_count(13:59) if data exists; otherwise mark delta as null.)\n3) Return the top 3 minutes with the largest positive minute_to_minute_delta (sorted by delta desc). For each of these top-3 minutes provide: minute_timestamp (ISO+08:00), anomalous_pairs_count, minute_to_minute_delta, and the top 5 cmdb_ids contributing anomalous pairs at that minute with counts formatted as cmdb_id:count (limit 5). \nKeep output compact (3 rows). Do not return raw time series. If global P95 per pair needs to be computed, compute it using the full available metric series before filtering to the window."
}

